{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_kloeden_ver01/data/sn85058393/print/1921032801/1238.xml":{"full_text":"'f.r tv.v' H\nEVENING. FEBRljHBHB\nilHiHHHHHIIHilHK qtawdard-examiner HIHIBMP\nI MONDAY EVENING, MARCH 28, 1921. iElW ttXUt WCblEXfflltl$ OGDEN, UTAH,\nI GHOIR FEATURES\"\nI EASTER SERVICE-\nI\nL Sacred Cantata Creates a\nVivid Impression of\nChrist's Crucifixion\nScenes from the world's great\nL tragedy, enacted on Calvary over nine-1\nfl leen hundred years ugo. were vividly\n:ind Impressively portrayed by the. Og-\nden tabernacle choir Sunday afternoon.\nIn the rendition of tho beautiful can-1\nlata. \"The Seven Iast Words of;\nV Christ.\" bv Theodore Dubois,\nUnder the direction of Joseph Bal\nr lantyne, with Sam F. Whitaker at tho\nnrgan, tho local musical organization. I\nin eolo and chorus told the story ofj\nI tho crucifixion of Christ. In a most,\nrealistic manner the scenes of the\ndreadful day were brought before the;\nlarge congregation that filled the tab\nernacle to overflowing\nIMPRESSIVE Si EN E\nThe great musical composition) as\ninterpreted by the choir and SOliSts\nmade a wonderful impression on the I\ncongregation. Perhaps the most thrill\ning moment was win n Win. S. Wright\nrendered In solo the prayer of Christ!\nFather, Forgive Them,\" and was re\nbuked by the choir, representing the\nrabble that gathered al Calvary shout-1\nlug in jeering tones, \"He Is Death\nfJullty, Take Him. Let Us Crucify\nHim.\"\nKqually Impressive was the interpre\ntation of the scene when Christ in a\ncry of agon said. \"I Thirst,\" and ihe\nrabble jeered at Him reminding Him\nof His claim to be able to destroy the\ntemple and raise up again In three\ndays.\nThe most intense moment in the(\nscene of the crucifixion was portrayed\nIn organ music which was realistic I\nind awe inspiring in its description of\niho three hours darkness when the\nearth quaked, the rocks were rent and\nthe graves were opened This scene\n.is Interpreted on the great organ by\nProfessor Whltaker in a wonderfully\nrealistic manner to which the large\ncongregation listened with rapt atten\ntion, filled the Inrflra auditorium with\nI sounds of rolling thunders, rushing\nwinds and rending roc Km\nB 1RKI K tm l S\nSoloists who rendered selections in\nthe cantata were Mrs. Myrtle B Uig\nley, Mrs. Agnes Warner, Miss Lorenc\nWhite. Mies Mildred Ware and William\n.s; Wright.\nThe service was conducted bj .ludgo\nGeorge S. Marker and the texl of the\ncantata was re.nl by Mrs. Bella S. Koss.\nInvocation by Alfred Oladwell.\nSunerintendent Adam S Bennlon ol\nthe Latter Hay Saint church schools\nWas the special speaker at the service.\nITc told 01 bis appreciation of the work\nol the choir and declared he could\nnot recall an occasion on which he\nwas thrilled as he had been during the\nrendition of the cantata by the choir.\nIn prlel talk with the choir at the\nconclusion of the service, Superintend\nent Kennion riald their work was won-\nrfUlly effective and extended an n\nvltatlon to the Choir to render the can\nTat i in Bait Lake. He said he would\nba glad to use hi:- Influence in hawing\nthe cantata rendered In the capital\ncity by the choir.\nGLORIES OF CHRIS1\nIn his address to the congregation.\nSuperintendent Bennlon spoke upon\nthe glories of Christ. He said Christ\nwas a Wonderful man He lived his\nlife in seclusion in the small country\nof Judea, was engaged In his public\nmission but three years and yet today\nstands out as the greatest character\nIn history.\nThe glories of Christ, he said, con\nsisted of his wonderful self-mastery,\nhis wonderful love and sacrifice.\nICaster, the speaker said, was a greater\nfestival than Christmas but it was al\nlowed to pass b) somewhat llghllx.\nWhat the world needs today, he said, Is\nmore of the spirit of Christ in the\nfields, the office, the workshop and the\nhome.\nno\nI NOTICE\nClearfield hall, Monday\nevening, 8:30. Special\n\"Huckleberry Finn\" and\nJack Dempsey. Same prices.\n1S3J\nMayor Outlines I\nHis Program For j\nImproving City\nDeclares He Will Continue\nFight for Light Plant;\nPower Company Prom\nises Improved\nFacilities\n\"While the municipal electric! light,\nheat and power plant proposal was\ndefeated Saturday. I feel that the veto\nIndicated a strong and positive senti\nment from the people In favor of Og\nden owning its lighting system.\" de\nclared Mayor Frank Francis this\nmorning, commenting upon lhe re\nsult of the municipal bond election.\nPersonally 1 consider this only the\nfirst battle and I will devote my efforts\nto a campaign ot education looking\nforward to the time when Ogden Will\nproceed to Install its own municipal\nplant and seive itself\n.folis FOR OGDEN1 PES\nMayor Francis announced that pi ana\nwill b begun tonight at the first com\nmission meeting since the election, to\ncarry through the Improvements voted\nfor by the people. He said that no\ntime will be lost In order that em\nployment may Be given to Ogden\nworkers First consideration will be\ngiven to men who have families and\nhomes hen and the contractors who\nhandle the contracts will be compelled\nto follow this plan, ho declared.\nMayor Francis said:\nM YOR'S PLANS\nAt tonight's commission meeting\nplans will be made for the advertising\nfor bids for sanitary -ewers Including\nthe outfall sewer so that work will be\nstarted as soon as possible. The cltj\nnow has availablo approximately $200,\niho in the treasury to cover first esti\nmates on this work The next move\nV. Ill DC IO MTU1C lljnia vmi fuw i v.\nfor a larger water supply and begin\nthe working out of extensions for a\nlarger distributive system Plans will\nalso be immediately made for the pav\ning ol upper Twenty-fifth street dis\ntrict, winch has been held up for three\nyears. There are also fifty-lWO blocks\nol sidewalks and many blocks of curb\ning and guttering, which will be gotten\nunder way During the past Winter\ncomplaints have been received owing\nto the bad conditions of sidewalks,\ncurbing and gutters, so this must be\ncorrected at once\nVVOID I KLTRAA IG VM Ii\n\"The general verdict of the people\nI look upon as a vote of confidence\nin that they authorized bonds to the\nextent of $1,410,000 In addition 'to\n1136,000 bonds previously authorized\nand Jim, nun in money that is now\navailable, making the greatest author\ni Ltion given any board of commisslon-\nn in the state of Utah. But the very\niact the amount Is o large means that\nwe must proceed with extreme caution\nand avoid any extravagance or reek\nleys expenditure of money. To guard\nagainst that I am looking forward to\nthe calling In of an advisory commit\ntee, composed of representatives of the\ndifferent elements of the community\nSpecial attention will be given to th\nneed of improvements and the beuring\nupon taxation.\n\"As announced before the election\nthere will be no thought of expenditure\nin great haste and the money will not\nbe spent In less time than five or six\nyears and will go to working out of\na cltv building system.\nSTRONG SENTIMENT\n\"While we were defeated on the\nelectric light and power proposal. I\nfeel that the vote indicates a strong\nand positive sentiment in favor of g\nden owning its lighting system Per\nsonally 1 consider this only the first\nbattle and I Will devote m efforts to\na campaign of education looking for\nward to the time when Ogden will pro\nceed to put in its own municipal plant\nand serve itself I am so thoroughly\na believer In the ultimate success of\n;this movement that I feel that the day\nis coming when Ogden will not only\nbe getting cheaper light service but\nthat this service will be so efficient\nand comparatively Inexpensive, that\nthe homes of the city will be heated by\nI PlayerRoll:\nI One Week Only i\nj Beginning today, and continuing through\nI this week, we are making a 25 per cent redur-\n1 tion on our entire surplus stock of player rolls.\nAmong them you will find some of the\nI choicest instrumental and vocal selections.\nI This is an excellent opportunity to add some\nf especially goods ones to your player roll library\nI and at the same time\nSave 25\nut3l Come in early tomorrow if possible before they're I\nY al picked over. Every selection, will bo played for\nH you, so you will be sure of getting .pisi what you\nH want. Remember, ihe week will soon go-r-so will I\nH the Player Rolls.\nI I Music Department\nI Last Thomas I\nlcclrlc energy s. ied by the munici\npal plain\nitegarding our developments of the\nwater .supply for ogden City, it will be\nrecalled that the city holds rights at\nSkull Crack on the South Pork of 1 g\n'don river Test pits for bedrock have\nI been sunk excepting for a distance r\nI five feet across this stream. We will\n(proceed at once to complete these test\npits, go details of construction can be\narranged.\nDISTRIB17I ING si sn M\n\"As to the distributive system, the\ncommissioners have plans well under\nway for Improvements which include\ntwo new main arteries, probably to\nextend to Thirty-second street and\nWall avenue, across the southeastern\nend of the city and to Twenty-first\nand \"Wall avenue, extending Just south\nOf the i Kden river\n\"As soon as we can get underway\nemployment will be given to a large\nj number of men In Ogden. Ileum\nowners and men with families will be\nconsidered first, then other I igden\nmen. before bringing in outside work\ners.. Contraotors will be compelled to\ni obligate thems' lves to curry out thl.s\nplan\nOFFICIAL Ki l l UN'S\nOfficial returns which were finally\ncompiled at 10:30 o'clock yesterday\nmorning when final reports had been\nmade by the five wards, showed that\nI the eb-ctrie light plant proposal wis\nI defeated by 142 votes. The figures\nI made apparent the fact that the bal\ni loting in the Fourth ward was re\ni sponsible for the final defeat. I he\nI First, Second and Third wards gave\nthe electric light item small favor\nable majorities, but the preponderance\nof votes in the Fourth and Fifth\nwards brought Its defeat\nP kRK T POP! i. LB\nThe item which went over with the\nI greatest majority was that for Instal\nlation of sanitary sewers. which\n'showed a majority of 763 votes Park\nimprovement vv a not popular and was\nthe it. m defeated with the greutcst\nmajority. Fire department improve-!\nmerit was not favorable and lost by\nI 203 votes\nCommissioner J. Ray Ward ex- i\nI pressed himself as greatly disappoint-1\ncd today as the result of ihe defeat\nof bonds for park and fire department\nImprovement.\nmm ii M i P IRK\nAs the result of the vote for parks\n'Commissioner Ward declared he will\nI recommend to the city commission\nthat Improvements at 1-orin Karr park\nI be abandoned and a sum taken from\nthe general fund to install an ath\nlctic field and playground at the\ncircus grounds at trie corner of Mon\nroe avenue and Twenty-ninth street\nHe said that $12,000 would provide\nbleachers, fences and all improve\nments and plans would be made to\nj make the park a place of beauty to the\nI district, rather than .an eyesore. lb\nasserted that his recommendation\nj will be that no money be spent at\nI Lorin Farr park this year for any\n1 purpose.\nj Commissioner Ward said the loca\nI tlon of tho proposed new athletic\nfield would be far better than that\nof Lorin Farr park for the reason that\nit would be near the high schools.\nCommissioner Ward declared he win\nexert all his influence to provide the\nnew field and playgrounds.\nI Survey Of the- final balloting for tbt\nj electric light plant shows that, the\nj Fourth ward voted 414 otes against\nI and 2S1 votes for the Item. This gave\na majority vote of 23 votes against\nthe bonds in this ward. The Flrft\nward voted a majority of To v otes for\nthe light bonds, the S6cond ward 46\nvotes for, and the Third ward. 8\nvotes against. The Fifth ward voted\n71 ballots majority against tin item.\n1 .1.1 A I 1 Ki s( l.i g\nResult of the election hovvs the fol\nlowing For. Against\nStorm sewers 124j 1081\nBridges L4.46 b&7\nPaving 1226 1005\nSidewalks 1203 Hi3-1\nCurbing 1 1' ti 2 1025\nSanitary sewers 1553 790\nWaterworks 13S.N 937\nRower plant 10?0 1232\nParks sic 1330\nFire apparatus Iu31 1234\nMERRILL'S s r. vi EMEN 1\nj. i-. .HL'iiiu, insiriei manager ior\nthe 1'iu.h l'ovva r vM- I,b.-bt Co. .sai.l\n'Of course It Is natural that wi I\nshould be very much gratified at the I\nnegative majority against the light i\nbonds.\n\"When we note that the sewer\nbonds were carried by a vote of more I\nthan two to one and that the samel\nballots registered a .substantial ma-''\njoritv against the lifhtlnn plant, we\nare impressed with the careful\ndiscrimination which was used by the\nvoters.\n\"Of course we look upon the results\nas a vote of confidence. We have\ntried to merit this in the past, and w\nShall, with renewed faith In the good\nwill of our ustomcru. endeavor to\njustify the same by our future course\nWhile our present faciities farl\nexcel! ans that igden might ev. r hope\nto obtain Independently, we arc now'\ndefinitely working on a plan which',\nwill materially improve them The I\nconfidence which our customers have,\nplaced in us, Will make it much easier!\nto obtain, for use al Ogden, the rela\ntively large amounts of money that I\nWill be necesaary.\"\nLOWER FREIGHT\nRATE, WESTS NEED\nPOCATELLO, Ida. March 28.\n\"Freight rates will hae lo come down\nto aid the return of prosperity in the\nwest,\" said United States Senator\nFrank Gooding who was in Pocatello\nyesterday en route from Washington\nto (Joodtng. where ho will spend the\nnext ten daj i\nHe said that the senate is doing\nwhat it can, but declared that the\n'urge for lower freight rales must\ncome from Ihe west itself.\nSenator Gooding expressed the opin\ni ion that the tariif measure i- the most\n1 important leeislation before the na\nj tion, and feels that it will do a great\ndeal towards stabilizing the financial\nconditions of the west.\noo\nNotice, I. O. O F.\nAll Odd Fellows are requested to\nI meet at Kirkendall undertaking par\nlors on Tuesday, March 2!, at 10 a.\nm., to attend the funeral of Brother\nGeorge W. Huff Henry Kissel. Sec\nretary. i\",i)ii\noo\nThe Savannah, first .steamship to\ncross tho Atlantic, was built in X. w\nYork and launched Aug 22. 181b.\nADD TO SCHOOL\nHN COUNTY\nj\nj Board of Education Plans1\n1 Additions at Plain City,\nWilson and Riverdale\ni\nAdditional class room at several of\nthe Count) schools Will be provided\nthis summer by the Weber COUUtS\nboard of education to relieve present\ncrowded conditions\nAt the regular meeting of tho\nhoard Saturday, it was voted to pro\nvide four-room additions to the Wil\nsem, I'biln city anil Kiverdale school-s\nthis season The) school architects.\nWoods ami Jensen, were athorized lo\ndraw complete: plans for such build\nings at once and submit the same to\nbid, so that the work may be com\nmenced and buildings constructed in\nlime for use next September.\nAt present tho Wilson school as\nconstructed is a four-room building,\nwhen completed In l'JO\" it afforded\nmore space than the school really i\nneeded. But today Wilson has enough\npupils for eight rooms and nine\nrooms, if the- ninth grade- is conducted\nthere, as contemplated. Two im\nprovised rooms are now In use In\nhall-ways, one other has been fixed\nUp for temporary use In the basement,\ni and a rented room from the church\nacross the street Is also being Utilised\nto meet the present congestion.\nThe board with Supu JJ A Fowler J\nhav Just completed a tour of lnspcc-i\ntion of all sehools of tho county ex-1\ncept the- valley schools, which they\nI will visit later. un this trip. the\nhave noted all mate-rial needs, and:\nI are devising ways anil means to meet\nthe pressing Improvements that have!\nbeen postponed until after war-Inflated\nprices have receded. They an\nconvinced, they said, that further de-I\nlay in enlarging buildings in five or;\nI six tow ns in tho county is Impossible,\nj Three schools will be Improved this!\nyear\n1 he towns that will receive con i\nslderation next year are Hooper ana i\npossibly Burcfa Creek.\nl nii i:i ULNMENT FACILITIES\nIt is planned to make arrangements,\n111 these neve bulblliiLfs So tbaf two'\nlarge rooms may be converted into\none by means of adjustable parti-\nHons,, so that assemblies, dances, en\ntertainments, operatlas and moving!\npictures may be conducted under lh:\ndirection of the school, without add\ning materially to the expense of the\nonstructlon. In most cases the audi\ntorium arrangements will be made- by\nusing folding or sliding doors in tht\ntwo upper rooms of the new building.!\nA hot lunch room and a shop room\nmay then be. provided in the basement\nby excavating under the four-room\nadditions.\nTho building committee consists of\nthe following members. W. strat\nford, chairman; John Halls, Thom.as\nI iJuclge. Joseph Skeen and John D.\nI Hooper.\noo\nRANDALL TELLS OF\nMISSIONARY WORK\nNKTH oGDEN\". March 28 David I\nK. l'au.lall, a fernier member of the\nbishopric of North ugden, who recent\nly returned from his second mission i\nlor the L. D. S. church to England,\nrelated his e xperiences at the- Sundaj\nmeetings In the ward chapel He also1\nJ spoke at the Ogtlen Stake union meet- t\nI ing at the Weber Normal college Sun\nday. A reception will be given in his\nI honor at the ward hall Wednesday.\nA farewell entertainment will he\ntendered Archie P. Clifford, Friday\nevening, before his departure for a\nmission in California.\nMrs JCmily L. Blaylock entertained\nSaturday evening in honor of her hus\nband, John y. Blaylock's 43rd birth\nday, at their home in North Ogden.\nThose present were Mr and Mrs.\nGeorge E, Brown, Mr and Mrs LJlsh\nI op Barker, Mr. and Mrs. Wm. A.\nMontgomery, Mr. and Mrs. Thomas\nI P. Barrett, Mr and Mrs Alfred Ford,\nMi ami Mrs Elijah baisbery, Mr. and\nI .Mrs H. F Blaylock, Mr and Mrs. A.\nG. Berrctt Mr. and Mrs Geo. Young-\nman. J. H Blaylock. Paul Blaylock,\nMiss Gladys Blaylock. Mrs. Annlo E.\nBerrett, Mr. and Mrs. John Q. Blay\nlock.\nWilliam L. Blaylock is confined to I\nhis home awaiting the healing o a\nI severe gash in his foot caused b an'\naccidental blow of an axe\n1178 CORRECT\nARSWERS TO TOE\nWW PUZZLE\nMany children were accurate in\nspelling ami framing the sentences, the\nfollowing having appeared frequently\nin our advertising\n\"Tho Alhambra Is Fire Proof, it is\na place- to send the children.\"\nApproximately 400 contestants fail\ned by Omission ot letters and aMilingj\nmore worels than the above sentences\nCOntftJhJ The passes will be mailed to\nday to the successful \"ones.\nBead them over carefully as the ex\nplanations are very plain and no epues- j\ntions need to be asked if you read I\nthem carefully.\nThe Alhambra Theati Co\nDANCE\nGiver, for the\nbenefit of\nOgden Baseball\nClub\nat die\nBERTHANA\nThursday Evening,\nMarch 31\nat 9 p. m.\nLillian Thatcher\nOrchestra\nAn Informal Event\nj\nI In\nNew Linoleums I\nA carload of the famous Armstrong's Linoleums just received, i In the shipment\nare parquetry inlaid3, first quality, straight line inlaids, Fulton inlaids, Acco inlaids,\nand a complete range of patterns in heavy and medium printed goods.\nlgp 1 Prices Are Down\npi y About One\nP\" Third -1\nBest inlaids selling recently at $7 00 I\nj T-ji- Per yard are now $5.40 L\nEtKjg $6 50 grade inlaids, now $4.50 I\nFy $5.25 grade inlaids, now $3.75\n$3.50 printed linoleums, now $2.60 U\nj rXilVi $3.25 printed linoleums, now $2.45\nr'.'CKr 'n addition to the reduction in price, the I\nJ. Amr quality of the goods is much better.\nDont hesitate to buy your linoleums now, the selections are at thciv best, the prices\nare reduced and we can lay the goods promptly. All our work guaranteed satis\nEfl factory.\nI 6 Patterns of \"E\" Print, very special, yd. $2.00 co\nARMSTRONG'S lp f -1 7f\nLINOLEUM RUGS I\na 4 new patterns just re B Js) 5L JS I I J Vzwl?\nceived in the 9x12 feet -S Amm W\nI size They sell for $22.50 EVERYTHING FOR THE HOME Ra\n1\nEARLY RESIDENT OF\nNORTH OGDEN DIES\nMrs Rachel Woodfleld, a resident\nof North Ogden since the early 50's,\ndied at noon Sunday of infirmities\nSho was 7-1 years old and was the\nWife of John 'oodfield.\nBorn at Burlington. Ia., May 17,\nthe daughter of William and Mary\nYnrwood lioylance, she came to (Jtafa\nwith her parents when she was 4 yeara\nold.\nThe family first lived in Salt Lake,\nbut later located at Mound Fort in\nogden and then at North Ogden\nOn her 17th birthday. May 1 7, 1865.\nshe was married to John Woodfleld.\na family of 12 children being born to\nthem.\nHor husband, a brother. James Roy\nlance and the following sons and\ndaughters survive, Mrs. Mary Dudman,\nElizabeth. John A. and William G\nWoodfleld of North Ogden. Mrs. Will\nlino A. Chad-wlck and Mis. Albert G.\nWard. Ogden valle Mrs Jerome\nMiller. Harrlsville; Mrs. Ward Fisher.\nFarr West; Mrs. William R. Mclntyre\nMrs. Norton Bow ns, and a number of\ngrnnd children and great grandchil\ndren. Funeral services will be held In the\nNorth Ogden ward chapel, p. m.\nWednesday Burial will be at North\nOgden.\nThe body may be viewed at the\nhome Tucsda and Wednesday. Flow\ners may be left at Rarkln Sons'\nchapel.\nSCARDINOS GO ON\nTRIAL TOMORROW\nTomorrow morning at 10 o'clock\niho ease of the state against John\nScardino, Josephine Scandino and\niheir daughter. Jennie Scardino. all\ncharged with murder in the first de\ngree for the alleged shooting of Mike\nTennaln here in February. 10, will\nopen in Judge George S Barker's dl\nision of the district court before a\nJury\nThe case is expected to attract rec\nord crowds to the court room for It\npromises to be of Intense interest\nthroughout Impaneling of the Jur\nw ill probably consume most of the\nsessions tomorrow and it i? not likely\nthai evidence taking will begin before\nWednesday morning. John Scardino,\nthe father of tho girl who liral ad\nmitted the shooting, is being held in\nthe county jail without bonds. Mrs\nScardino and her daughter are al lib\nerty under heavy bonds.\nGeorge Halverson, Ogden attorn--;\nwill represent the defendants, while\nDistrict Attorney Joseph E. Evans will\nhandle the prosecution.\n43 CARS INCLUDED\nIN STOCK SHIPMENT\nForty-three carp of cattle and hops\nwere included in sauss and shipments\njat tho Ogden Union Stockyards since\nSaturday. They were:\nBaUser Racking company. Ixs An\ngeles. 12 ears cattle.\nWestern Mc:it company, San Fran\ncisco, 7 cars cattle.\nVerdin Packing company. San Fran\ncisco, j cars cattle and 4 cars hogs,\nj Western Meat company. San Fran\ncisco. 7 cars hogs.\nOakland Meat company. 3 cars hogs.\nOgden Racking company, cars\nhogs.\noo\ni The British railways employ 10.00C\nfi mule clurks.\nFORD TOPS LIST\nIN TRAP EYENT\nComes Out High Gun in\n50 Bird Event; Ties\nin Doubles\nFrnle Ford topped the Ogden Gun!\nclub shoob-rs in the \"Easter\" lmot\nheld at the traps at the Ogden Country\nclub yesterday morning Ford was high\ngun in the \".0 blrrl cent smashing 17\nfrom the lti yard line. In this eent\nGuy Dahl was a close second with a\ni score of 46 while Tony Shufflebarger\nwas third with a score of 4j.\nIn the doubles events Ford and DahJ\n'tied for first honors each having broke\n19 out of a possible 26 Hlnlej finish-,\nled third In this event and Rrnney'\nj fourth.\nFollowing are the scores.\nShot at Broke\nErnie Ford ....50 47\nDahl 50 4f.\nShufflebarger 50 4o\nIClark 50 44 1\nDr. G. Baker 50 42\nLowe 50 40\nWelling 50 86:\nDOUBLES\nShot at Broke\nFord 2G 19'\nI Dahl 25 19\nHinley .25 is\nDraney 25 17\nShufflebarger 25 17\nI Clark 25 15,\ni Baker 25 U\noo I\nSHOWER GIFTS ON\nSICK COMPANIONS\nI The practical religion taught to\nchildren by the Religion classes of the\n1, D. S, church was demonstrated\ni Easter Sunday morning when the third\nand fourth grades of the organization\nat the Fourteenth ward paid a visit,\nto two of their sick members.\nIn charge of the teachers the chil-l\ndren visited Erma Garner, a daughter\nof Mr. and Mrs F. L. Garner and Rob-i\nert Stevens, a son of Mr. and Mrs Alex\nStevens, who have been ill for several\nweeks. Carrying With them baskets'\nfilled with Easter eggs and other good;\nthings, the children entered the two\nhomes and sttowered Iheir gifts upon\ntheir Bit k companions. The littb br.\nand piri who through iiin--.-s have been\nunable to attend sessions of the organ-J\nIzatlon for some time, were made\nCheerful by the visit of their class\nmates.\nUH GOING i\nTO CMNf 3\ncon\ncat.\nMan Who Fired County Ja\nRecovers From Tempo- ,-,J\nrary Derangement\nthe\n\"image to the interior of the calK\nty jail caused Saturday evrnli witl\nthrough the setting afire to the p cou\nding ot a spei inl i ll by Antonio II dlar\nlion, a di ianm-d inmate, v. ill lota a Pa\nprnximah-ly Slmm according to an v\nlunate made this niornincr by Sheri oral\nRichard Pincock The loss is co 11111\ncred by insurance, he said. c\nThe interior of the padded refl aj\na I.ul'c room in vhi h the cell is co m;i\ntained, was completely ruined, ineli con\ning two doors and frames on adjoins\ni. \"in. The fiTllnc of the corridor W rail\ndamaged and electric lmht fixtui t'ni\nburned da\nHernon, who caused the fire, Ik'\npeared rational yesterday and wllu E:\ntaken to San Fr. m i-. L tonight, It 1\na i el s on his w;i lo Callflj cre(\nni.i a da;. zo when taken ir a\na 'ram due to bi p 1 iliar action.. ajtri\nwould give the oiiieers no inforn\ntlon as to where he obtained I B\nmati h cstf-nla. but it is belief\nthat he picked it from the floor whl jV\nformer lodgers had dropped It. pert\noo\nGLOBE MILL FILES\nSUIT FOR $381 pa0;.1\nforr\nthe\nSuit to recover $3820.95 has be cor,\nfiled in the district court by the GlO a a\nGrain Milling company against arhl\nDavid Leigh The amount is alles men\nto be due for merchandise delher, (ltlr:\nby the plaintiff.\nuvi .hl.\nNORTH OGDEN CHOIR\nSINGS EASTER SONG ?t\npror\nBefore a large attendance, Ce.fj\nNorth Ogden ward choir delivered!\n.lain. late pioram ot Faster mil nisei\nSundaj night. Knur hundred filt;- p ers\nsons were present COur\nDavid B Randall, a returned in and\nrelati I nine int. r --tins\nperlenees In Ncv.-castle. Wales n 1\nmini\nJffif. Time To Change\n5 Underwear?\ndfkd\nTjU I rcHE heavy woolens of Win-\nV ,J ter are ready for the dts- JJjJ\nPl card. With balmy Spring and\nevery man desires a change to r\nV lighter and finer ldnd of Under- JJJ\nwear. Here you will find the ;i b\nj kind of Underwear that good\nI) dressers have been wearing for\nT7 years the preference of men of a\ntA active habits. It is the kind that A\n4Sf insures the utmost satisfaction,\nparticularly in comfort at all Jtnc:\ntimes. Full length, three quar- Jf\nter length or union Suits are here. Jj c\n'e n\nI b;it,\nii r.hv\nI we r","height":"27156","width":"19596"}}
